	(181, 1, 'Botble\\ACL\\Models\\User', 'post', '{"name":"Does AI Owe You? (Axios AM)","model":"Botble\\\\Blog\\\\Models\\\\Post","slug":"exploring-the-benefits-of-mysql-for-large-scale-projects","slug_id":"25","is_slug_editable":"1","description":"A deep dive into whether individuals should be compensated when their online content\\u2014social posts, blogs, other digital contributions\\u2014is used without consent to train AI models.","is_featured":"0","content":"<p style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;margin:0px;padding:0px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">You could easily<\\/strong> live without AI. But AI wouldn\'t exist without you, <em style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\"><i>Jim VandeHei and Mike Allen write in a \\"Behind the Curtain\\" column.<\\/i><\\/em><\\/p><ul style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;list-style:none url(&quot;https:\\/\\/static.axios.com\\/img\\/axios-site\\/bullet-filled.svg&quot;);margin:0px;padding:0px 0px 0px 18px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">So does AI owe you<\\/strong> for your small part in creating it?<\\/li><\\/ul><p style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;margin:0px;padding:0px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">Why it matters: <\\/strong>This question sits at the very heart of legal, economic, moral and societal debates unfolding before us today \\u2014 and deep into the future. The answer will unlock everything from court verdicts to the fortunes of financial winners and losers years from now.<\\/p><p style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;margin:0px;padding:0px;word-spacing:0px;\\">\\ud83d\\uddbc\\ufe0f <strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">The big picture:<\\/strong> First, the facts. Large language models (LLMs) such as OpenAI\'s ChatGPT or Anthropic\'s Claude were built by ingesting the totality of human information online \\u2014 everything from news stories by Axios to social media postings by you.<\\/p><ul style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;list-style:none url(&quot;https:\\/\\/static.axios.com\\/img\\/axios-site\\/bullet-filled.svg&quot;);margin:0px;padding:0px 0px 0px 18px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:12px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">AI developers call<\\/strong> this \\"training data\\" because they used the internet \\u2014 and all its content \\u2014 to train machines to think, reason and operate like the humans feeding the web.&nbsp;The goal: think better, faster and cheaper than us. Then, unleash these machines everywhere for everything.<\\/li><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">By 2025,<\\/strong> content produced by billions of internet users helped shape the massive digital corpus that modern AI models were trained on \\u2014 mostly through public, web-accessible data. Think any content \\u2014 posts, blogs, forums, websites, Wikipedia edits, reviews, and videos.<\\/li><\\/ul><p style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;margin:0px;padding:0px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">Some content owners<\\/strong> \\u2014 mass producers and individual creators \\u2014 are suing AI companies for using their content without permission. The litigation \\u2014 by media companies, music producers, book publishers \\u2014 is often brought under copyright laws. AI makers defend their use of protected content by invoking long-contested \\"fair use\\" principles.<\\/p><ul style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;list-style:none url(&quot;https:\\/\\/static.axios.com\\/img\\/axios-site\\/bullet-filled.svg&quot;);margin:0px;padding:0px 0px 0px 18px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:12px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">Copyright owners<\\/strong> have filed close to 50 lawsuits against AI companies in federal court, according to the <a class=\\"gtmContentClick\\" style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(34,87,218);font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\" href=\\"https:\\/\\/copyrightalliance.org\\/ai-copyright-infringement-cases-insights\\/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener\\">Copyright Alliance<\\/a>, which <a class=\\"gtmContentClick\\" style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(34,87,218);font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\" href=\\"https:\\/\\/copyrightalliance.org\\/about\\/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener\\">represents creators<\\/a>.<\\/li><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><a class=\\"gtmContentClick\\" style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(34,87,218);font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\" href=\\"https:\\/\\/copyrightalliance.org\\/artificial-intelligence-copyright\\/licensing\\/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">Some publishers<\\/strong><\\/a><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">,<\\/strong> including <a class=\\"gtmContentClick\\" style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(34,87,218);font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\" href=\\"https:\\/\\/investors.newscorp.com\\/news-releases\\/news-release-details\\/news-corp-and-openai-sign-landmark-multi-year-global-partnership\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener\\">News Corp<\\/a> and <a class=\\"gtmContentClick\\" style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(34,87,218);font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\" href=\\"https:\\/\\/openai.com\\/index\\/partnering-with-axios-expands-openai-work-with-the-news-industry\\/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener\\">Axios<\\/a>, have struck deals with OpenAI for use of their content.<\\/li><\\/ul><p style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;margin:0px;padding:0px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">The Supreme Court could<\\/strong> ultimately decide \\u2014 likely years from now \\u2014 whether the owners of these LLMs violated federal law with their training tactics.<\\/p><ul style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;list-style:none url(&quot;https:\\/\\/static.axios.com\\/img\\/axios-site\\/bullet-filled.svg&quot;);margin:0px;padding:0px 0px 0px 18px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">\\"We\'re at the top<\\/strong> of the first inning of understanding how the courts are going to define fair use as it applies to AI training,\\" <a class=\\"gtmContentClick\\" style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(34,87,218);font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\" href=\\"https:\\/\\/copyrightalliance.org\\/about\\/keith-kupferschmid\\/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener\\">Keith Kupferschmid<\\/a>, president and CEO of the Copyright Alliance, tells us. He said cases involving images and music will be more difficult for AI companies to win, while cases involving text are more complex.<\\/li><\\/ul><p style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;margin:0px;padding:0px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">But what about <\\/strong><em style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\"><i><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">you?<\\/strong><\\/i><\\/em><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\"> <\\/strong>If you ever posted a comment on Reddit, or tweeted, or shared pictures on Instagram, or posted a rant on Facebook, you\'re a tiny part of the LLMs\' brains.<\\/p><ul style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;list-style:none url(&quot;https:\\/\\/static.axios.com\\/img\\/axios-site\\/bullet-filled.svg&quot;);margin:0px;padding:0px 0px 0px 18px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">Your words were<\\/strong> gobbled up to help train the machines, creating untold riches for tech companies and investors. But no one asked your permission or offered to compensate for that tiny part you played in making others rich.<\\/li><\\/ul><p style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;margin:0px;padding:0px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">It\'s doubtful<\\/strong> you\'ll get a penny for your time or mind now. President Trump, in his speech at last month\'s <a class=\\"gtmContentClick\\" style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(34,87,218);font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\" href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/watch?v=tBNX9x5GgPE\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener\\">AI summit<\\/a> in Washington, made plain his opposition to companies doling out cash based on derivative use of the internet (unless it\'s blatant piracy).<\\/p><ul style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;list-style:none url(&quot;https:\\/\\/static.axios.com\\/img\\/axios-site\\/bullet-filled.svg&quot;);margin:0px;padding:0px 0px 0px 18px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:12px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">\\"[W]hen you read<\\/strong> something and when it goes into this vast intelligence <em style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\"><i>machine, <\\/i><\\/em>we\'ll call it, you cannot expect to every time, every single time, say: \'Oh, let\'s pay this one that much,\'\\" <a class=\\"gtmContentClick\\" style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(34,87,218);font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\" href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.techpolicy.press\\/transcript-donald-trumps-address-at-winning-the-ai-race-event\\/\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"noreferrer noopener\\">he said<\\/a>. \\"[W]e have to allow AI to use that pool of knowledge without going through the complexity of contract negotiations, of which there would be <em style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\"><i>thousands<\\/i><\\/em> for every time we use AI.\\"<\\/li><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">His main point:<\\/strong> It would give China an insurmountable edge if we tie ourselves in knots over who owes what to whom.<\\/li><\\/ul><p style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;margin:0px;padding:0px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">But some AI leaders, <\\/strong>most notably Anthropic\'s Dario Amodei, <a class=\\"gtmContentClick\\" style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(34,87,218);font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\" href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.axios.com\\/2025\\/05\\/28\\/ai-jobs-white-collar-unemployment-anthropic\\">argue you should benefit<\\/a> \\u2014 in the future. They believe if AI only enriches the big companies and investors, America will face a rebellion \\u2014 and potentially sky-high unemployment.<\\/p><ul style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;list-style:none url(&quot;https:\\/\\/static.axios.com\\/img\\/axios-site\\/bullet-filled.svg&quot;);margin:0px;padding:0px 0px 0px 18px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:12px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">So instead of <\\/strong>paying you now, which might hamstring the companies, they talk of spreading the wealth if AI truly creates trillions of dollars of wealth long-term. This could be as novel as a guaranteed minimum income (universal basic income, or UBI), funded by AI companies, or as ordinary as higher taxes on AI to fund social programs and government overall.<\\/li><li style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin-bottom:0px;margin-right:0px;margin-top:24px;padding:0px 0px 0px 8px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">Or it could be<\\/strong> a private sector indirect benefit of higher growth, driving higher wages.<\\/li><\\/ul><p style=\\"border-style:solid;color:rgb(51,51,53);font-family:Atiza, serif;font-size:18px;font-style:normal;font-weight:400;margin:0px;padding:0px;word-spacing:0px;\\"><strong style=\\"border-style:solid;font-family:Atiza, serif;margin:0px;padding:0px;\\">Regardless,<\\/strong> the AI companies will get a lot bigger and a lot richer \\u2014 before you get a penny, if you ever do.<\\/p><p>&nbsp;<\\/p>","gallery":null,"seo_meta":{"seo_title":null,"seo_description":null,"index":"index"},"seo_meta_image":null,"status":"published","categories":["4"],"image":"code\\/blog\\/blog01.jpg","tag":"[{\\"value\\":\\"Vietnam Developer\\"}]","allow_comments":"0"}', 'updated', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/138.0.0.0 Safari/537.36', '127.0.0.1', 1, 'Botble\\ACL\\Models\\User', 8, 'Does AI Owe You? (Axios AM)', 'primary', '2025-08-07 03:42:01', '2025-08-07 03:42:01'),
	(182, 1, 'Botble\\ACL\\Models\\User', 'post', '{"name":"Does AI Owe You? (Axios AM)","model":"Botble\\\\Blog\\\\Models\\\\Post","slug":"exploring-the-benefits-of-mysql-for-large-scale-projects","slug_id":"25","is_slug_editable":"1","description":"A deep dive into whether individuals should be compensated when their online content\\u2014social posts, blogs, other digital contributions\\u2014is used without consent to train AI models.","is_featured":"0","content":"<p>You could easily live without AI. But AI wouldn\'t exist without you, Jim VandeHei and Mike Allen write in a \\"Behind the Curtain\\" column. So does AI owe you for your small part in creating it? Why it matters: This question sits at the very heart of legal, economic, moral and societal debates unfolding before us today \\u2014 and deep into the future. The answer will unlock everything from court verdicts to the fortunes of financial winners and losers years from now. \\ud83d\\uddbc\\ufe0f The big picture: First, the facts. Large language models (LLMs) such as OpenAI\'s ChatGPT or Anthropic\'s Claude were built by ingesting the totality of human information online \\u2014 everything from news stories by Axios to social media postings by you. AI developers call this \\"training data\\" because they used the internet \\u2014 and all its content \\u2014 to train machines to think, reason and operate like the humans feeding the web. The goal: think better, faster and cheaper than us. Then, unleash these machines everywhere for everything. By 2025, content produced by billions of internet users helped shape the massive digital corpus that modern AI models were trained on \\u2014 mostly through public, web-accessible data. Think any content \\u2014 posts, blogs, forums, websites, Wikipedia edits, reviews, and videos. Some content owners \\u2014 mass producers and individual creators \\u2014 are suing AI companies for using their content without permission. The litigation \\u2014 by media companies, music producers, book publishers \\u2014 is often brought under copyright laws. AI makers defend their use of protected content by invoking long-contested \\"fair use\\" principles. Copyright owners have filed close to 50 lawsuits against AI companies in federal court, according to the Copyright Alliance, which represents creators. Some publishers, including News Corp and Axios, have struck deals with OpenAI for use of their content. The Supreme Court could ultimately decide \\u2014 likely years from now \\u2014 whether the owners of these LLMs violated federal law with their training tactics. \\"We\'re at the top of the first inning of understanding how the courts are going to define fair use as it applies to AI training,\\" Keith Kupferschmid, president and CEO of the Copyright Alliance, tells us. He said cases involving images and music will be more difficult for AI companies to win, while cases involving text are more complex. But what about you? If you ever posted a comment on Reddit, or tweeted, or shared pictures on Instagram, or posted a rant on Facebook, you\'re a tiny part of the LLMs\' brains. Your words were gobbled up to help train the machines, creating untold riches for tech companies and investors. But no one asked your permission or offered to compensate for that tiny part you played in making others rich. It\'s doubtful you\'ll get a penny for your time or mind now. President Trump, in his speech at last month\'s AI summit in Washington, made plain his opposition to companies doling out cash based on derivative use of the internet (unless it\'s blatant piracy). \\"[W]hen you read something and when it goes into this vast intelligence machine, we\'ll call it, you cannot expect to every time, every single time, say: \'Oh, let\'s pay this one that much,\'\\" he said. \\"[W]e have to allow AI to use that pool of knowledge without going through the complexity of contract negotiations, of which there would be thousands for every time we use AI.\\" His main point: It would give China an insurmountable edge if we tie ourselves in knots over who owes what to whom. But some AI leaders, most notably Anthropic\'s Dario Amodei, argue you should benefit \\u2014 in the future. They believe if AI only enriches the big companies and investors, America will face a rebellion \\u2014 and potentially sky-high unemployment. So instead of paying you now, which might hamstring the companies, they talk of spreading the wealth if AI truly creates trillions of dollars of wealth long-term. This could be as novel as a guaranteed minimum income (universal basic income, or UBI), funded by AI companies, or as ordinary as higher taxes on AI to fund social programs and government overall. Or it could be a private sector indirect benefit of higher growth, driving higher wages. Regardless, the AI companies will get a lot bigger and a lot richer \\u2014 before you get a penny, if you ever do. Share this column.<\\/p>","gallery":null,"seo_meta":{"seo_title":null,"seo_description":null,"index":"index"},"seo_meta_image":null,"status":"published","categories":["4"],"image":"code\\/blog\\/blog01.jpg","tag":"[{\\"value\\":\\"Vietnam Developer\\"}]","allow_comments":"0","submitter":"apply"}', 'updated', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/138.0.0.0 Safari/537.36', '127.0.0.1', 1, 'Botble\\ACL\\Models\\User', 8, 'Does AI Owe You? (Axios AM)', 'primary', '2025-08-07 03:42:49', '2025-08-07 03:42:49'),
	(183, 1, 'Botble\\ACL\\Models\\User', 'post', '{"name":"AI-Driven Coding Revolution: From Vibe Coding to Agentic Agents in 2025","model":"Botble\\\\Blog\\\\Models\\\\Post","slug":"my-journey-in-open-source-3-years-of-contributions","slug_id":"19","is_slug_editable":"1","description":"A forward-looking exploration of AI\\u2019s latest breakthroughs in software engineering: from vibe coding and agentic agents to the imminent GPT\\u20115 launch and the tools redefining what it means to be a programmer in 2025.","is_featured":"0","content":"<hr><h3>1. <strong>The New AI Frontier: GPT\\u20115 and Agentic Coding Agents<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>OpenAI is poised to unveil <strong>GPT\\u20115<\\/strong>, with four model variants offering enhanced reasoning, complex task execution, and deeper code understanding through test\\u2011time compute integration. Early leaks suggest powerful agentic capabilities and multi-scale deployment options, including mini and nano versions for flexible API use (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.reuters.com\\/business\\/retail-consumer\\/openais-long-awaited-gpt-5-model-nears-release-2025-08-06\\/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"OpenAI\'s long-awaited GPT-5 model nears release\\">Reuters<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.theverge.com\\/news\\/752091\\/openai-gpt-5-model-announcement-github-leak?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"OpenAI\'s new GPT-5 models announced early by GitHub\\">The Verge<\\/a>).<br>Alongside, <strong>Anthropic released Claude Opus\\u202f4.1<\\/strong>, pushing performance on coding, reasoning, and creative writing fronts (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/economictimes.indiatimes.com\\/tech\\/artificial-intelligence\\/anthropic-releases-claude-opus-4-1-amid-rival-chatgpts-advancements\\/articleshow\\/123143392.cms?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Anthropic releases Claude Opus 4.1 amid rival ChatGPT\'s advancements\\">The Economic Times<\\/a>).<\\/p><h3>2. <strong>Vibe Coding vs. Agentic Coding: The Two Paradigms<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>The newly coined <strong>vibe coding<\\/strong> method\\u2014a prompt-driven workflow where developers describe software in natural language and iteratively refine output\\u2014has surged in popularity. Major platforms like Airtable, Meta, and Reddit now seek expertise in this style (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.businessinsider.com\\/vibe-coding-limits-use-cases-software-companies-airtable-redis-2025-7?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Vibe coding is the future &amp;mdash; just don\'t trust it (yet)\\">Business Insider<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/Vibe_coding?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Vibe coding\\">Wikipedia<\\/a>).<br>By contrast, <strong>agentic coding<\\/strong> refers to autonomous AI agents capable of planning, testing, and adapting software tasks with minimal human oversight. A recent taxonomy explores how these paradigms support everything from prototyping to enterprise-level CI\\/CD automation (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/arxiv.org\\/abs\\/2505.19443?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Vibe Coding vs. Agentic Coding: Fundamentals and Practical Implications of Agentic AI\\">arXiv<\\/a>).<\\/p><h3>3. <strong>Industry Shift: Developers, Meet Copilot Agents<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>GitHub\\u2019s CEO Thomas Dohmke declared: \\u201c<strong>Embrace AI or get out<\\/strong>.\\u201d He defines the new developer role as code <i>enabler<\\/i> or <i>creative director<\\/i>, overseeing AI-generated solutions rather than writing every line manually. The message is clear\\u2014this transformation is required, not optional (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.businessinsider.com\\/github-ceo-developers-embrace-ai-or-get-out-2025-8?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"GitHub CEO delivers stark message to developers: Embrace AI or get out.\\">Business Insider<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/timesofindia.indiatimes.com\\/education\\/news\\/either-embrace-ai-or-get-out-of-your-career-says-github-ceo-thomas-dohmke-heres-what-software-professionals-need-to-know\\/articleshow\\/123155980.cms?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"&quot;Either embrace AI or get out of your career,&quot; says GitHub CEO Thomas Dohmke: Here\'s what software professionals need to know\\">The Times of India<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.redhotcyber.com\\/en\\/post\\/github-ceo-programmers-who-dont-embrace-ai-will-be-done\\/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"GitHub CEO: Programmers Who Don\\u2019t Embrace AI Will Be Done\\">Red Hot Cyber<\\/a>).<br>Copilot has also evolved into a multitasking coding agent capable of running background tasks and auto\\u2011generating repository-specific instructions through custom plug\\u2011ins and repository workflows (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/github.blog\\/changelog\\/2025-08-06-copilot-coding-agent-automatically-generate-custom-instructions\\/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Copilot coding agent: Automatically generate custom instructions\\">The GitHub Blog<\\/a>).<\\/p><h3>4. <strong>Top AI Coding Tools Transforming Workflows<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>Leading platforms in 2025 include:<\\/p><ul><li><strong>GitHub Copilot<\\/strong>, for in-editor code suggestions integrated deeply into DevOps pipelines.<\\/li><li><strong>Tabnine<\\/strong>, favored for local deployment and privacy-first environments.<\\/li><li><strong>Amazon CodeWhisperer<\\/strong>, optimized for AWS-centric enterprise applications.<br>Other contenders like Knack, Bolt, Cursor, v0, Lovable, Replit, and Windsurf continue diversifying options through specialized and low\\u2011code tooling (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/division5.co\\/blog\\/ai-powered-coding-tools-boosting-software-development-2025\\/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"AI-Powered Coding Tools: Boosting Software Development in 2025\\">division5<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.knack.com\\/blog\\/top-ai-coding-tools-2025\\/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Top 10 AI Coding Tools to Use (2025 Guide) - knack.com\\">Knack<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/blog.seeb4coding.in\\/the-future-of-coding-best-ai-tools-in-2025\\/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"The Future of Coding: Best AI Tools in 2025 - blog.seeb4coding.in\\">blog.seeb4coding.in<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/dev.to\\/gocodeo\\/the-best-ai-for-coding-in-2025-3mka?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"The best AI for coding in 2025 - DEV Community\\">DEV Community<\\/a>).<\\/li><\\/ul><h3>5. <strong>Innovations in AI-Driven Algorithm Discovery<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>Enter <strong>AlphaEvolve<\\/strong>, DeepMind\\u2019s Gemini-powered agent that autonomously invents and refines algorithms through evolutionary model variations and evaluation-based selection\\u2014marking a leap toward autonomous scientific coding beyond domain-specific solutions (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/AlphaEvolve?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"AlphaEvolve\\">Wikipedia<\\/a>).<\\/p><h3>6. <strong>The Infrastructure Shift: Model Context Protocol Adoption<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>OpenAI\\u2014and others like Replit and Sourcegraph\\u2014have adopted the new <strong>Model Context Protocol (MCP)<\\/strong>, ensuring standardized interoperability between AI models and tools. Gemini model support from DeepMind indicates broad industry movement toward open agentic architectures (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/Model_Context_Protocol?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Model Context Protocol\\">Wikipedia<\\/a>).<\\/p><h3>7. <strong>Workforce Impact: Philosophers and Logical Thinkers Rise<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>Tech pioneer Tom Gruber (co-creator of Siri) predicts that traditional coding jobs may decline, while roles emphasizing critical reasoning, systemic thinking, and AI governance\\u2014and ironically, philosophy\\u2014will rise in value as GenAI handles syntax-heavy tasks (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.theaustralian.com.au\\/business\\/siri-cocreator-tom-gruber-says-critical-thinking-philosophers-will-get-the-jobs-in\\/news-story\\/33de575417aabce649fd760d84e32599?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Philosophers tipped to oust coding nerds in AI future\\">The Australian<\\/a>).<\\/p><hr><h3>\\ud83e\\udded <strong>Key Takeaways for Developers<\\/strong><\\/h3><figure class=\\"table\\"><table><thead><tr><th>Focus Area<\\/th><th>Why It Matters<\\/th><\\/tr><\\/thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Master prompt design &amp; vibe workflows<\\/strong><\\/td><td>To guide AI tools effectively and retain control over generated code<\\/td><\\/tr><tr><td><strong>Understand agentic lifecycle<\\/strong><\\/td><td>Agents can take on planning, testing, and deployment autonomously<\\/td><\\/tr><tr><td><strong>Prioritize human oversight<\\/strong><\\/td><td>Automated code needs review for architecture, security, and quality<\\/td><\\/tr><tr><td><strong>Stay infrastructure-savvy<\\/strong><\\/td><td>Embrace protocols like MCP to connect multi-model tools<\\/td><\\/tr><tr><td><strong>Develop critical thinking skills<\\/strong><\\/td><td>Logic, reasoning, and AI ethics increasingly define success<\\/td><\\/tr><\\/tbody><\\/table><\\/figure><hr><h3><strong>Looking Ahead<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>The software development landscape in 2025 is now defined by a symbiosis between developers and AI. Whether through vibe\\u2011driven prototyping or agentic automation pipelines, the key is not to resist AI\\u2014but to <strong>orchestrate it wisely<\\/strong>. Programming careers will focus on strategy, system design, and oversight over machine-generated code.<br>As <strong>GPT\\u20115<\\/strong>, <strong>Claude Opus 4.1<\\/strong>, and <strong>AlphaEvolve<\\/strong> reshape the pipeline, the future belongs to creative coders who can harness these tools not just to write code\\u2014but to <strong>orchestrate systems that generate code intelligently<\\/strong>.<\\/p><hr><p>Let me know if you\'d like code samples, tool comparisons, or interview insights on any of these topics.<\\/p><ul><li><a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.reuters.com\\/business\\/retail-consumer\\/openais-long-awaited-gpt-5-model-nears-release-2025-08-06\\/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\">Reuters<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.theverge.com\\/news\\/752091\\/openai-gpt-5-model-announcement-github-leak?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\">The Verge<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.businessinsider.com\\/github-ceo-developers-embrace-ai-or-get-out-2025-8?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\">Business Insider<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\"https:\\/\\/economictimes.indiatimes.com\\/tech\\/artificial-intelligence\\/anthropic-releases-claude-opus-4-1-amid-rival-chatgpts-advancements\\/articleshow\\/123143392.cms?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\">The Economic Times<\\/a><\\/li><\\/ul>","gallery":null,"seo_meta":{"seo_title":null,"seo_description":null,"index":"index"},"seo_meta_image":null,"status":"published","categories":["7","9"],"image":"code\\/blog\\/blog02.jpg","tag":"[{\\"value\\":\\"Full Stack Development\\"},{\\"value\\":\\"GitHub Projects\\"}]","allow_comments":"0","submitter":"apply"}', 'updated', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/138.0.0.0 Safari/537.36', '127.0.0.1', 1, 'Botble\\ACL\\Models\\User', 2, 'AI-Driven Coding Revolution: From Vibe Coding to Agentic Agents in 2025', 'primary', '2025-08-07 03:59:41', '2025-08-07 03:59:41'),
	(184, 1, 'Botble\\ACL\\Models\\User', 'post', '{"name":"How to Integrate APIs in Node.js for Your Next Project","model":"Botble\\\\Blog\\\\Models\\\\Post","slug":"how-to-integrate-apis-in-nodejs-for-your-next-project","slug_id":"26","is_slug_editable":"1","description":"A deep dive into the latest AI\\u2011powered coding trends dominating mid\\u20112025\\u2014from the rise of \\u201cvibe coding\\u201d and personalized AI IDEs to autonomous agentic workflows and the shifting roles of developers in this new paradigm.","is_featured":"1","content":"<h3>1. <strong>Vibe Coding: Creativity over Syntax<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>The concept of <strong>vibe coding<\\/strong>, introduced by Andrej Karpathy in early 2025, has taken off. It empowers developers to describe software in natural language and let LLMs generate most of the code, with humans iteratively refining it (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/zh.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/Vibe_coding?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Vibe coding\\">Wikipedia<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.glbgpt.com\\/blog\\/ai-vibe-coding-trends-2025-boosting-creativity-and-collaboration\\/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Exploring the Hottest AI Vibe Coding Trends in 2025\\">GLB-GPT<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/vibecodingguru.com\\/2025-ai-coding-trends\\/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"2025 AI Coding Trends - Vibe Coding Guru\\">vibecodingguru.com<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.inc.com\\/ben-sherry\\/the-vibe-coding-companies-and-founders-to-watch-in-2025\\/91221111?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"The Vibe Coding Companies and Founders to Watch in 2025\\">Inc.com<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.businessinsider.com\\/vibe-coding-limits-use-cases-software-companies-airtable-redis-2025-7?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Vibe coding is the future &amp;mdash; just don\'t trust it (yet)\\">Business Insider<\\/a>). While it\'s widely adopted for prototyping and rapid iteration by companies like Airbnb, Reddit, Visa, and Redis, critics warn about reliability and architectural limitations. CEOs emphasize that human oversight remains vital to maintain quality and prevent hidden vulnerabilities (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.businessinsider.com\\/vibe-coding-limits-use-cases-software-companies-airtable-redis-2025-7?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Vibe coding is the future &amp;mdash; just don\'t trust it (yet)\\">Business Insider<\\/a>).<\\/p><h3>2. <strong>Explosive Growth of Agentic Coding Tools<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>According to Jellyfish, adoption of <strong>agentic AI coding tools<\\/strong> jumped from 50% to 82% within six months, with AI-driven code reviews leaping to 76% usage (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.businessinsider.com\\/ai-coding-agents-adoption-top-tools-2025-8?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"AI coding agents are infiltrating the corporate world. Here are the top tools.\\">Business Insider<\\/a>). Fully autonomous pipelines\\u2014where AI actually authors and submits code\\u2014are still in early stages (about 8% of firms), but growing rapidly. Tools like GitHub Copilot Reviewer, Cursor BugBot, and CodeRabbit are leading this charge (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.businessinsider.com\\/ai-coding-agents-adoption-top-tools-2025-8?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"AI coding agents are infiltrating the corporate world. Here are the top tools.\\">Business Insider<\\/a>).<\\/p><h3>3. <strong>Personalized IDEs that Learn You<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>Next\\u2011gen IDEs are evolving to understand individual coding styles, predict bugs, suggest fixes, and embed custom shortcuts through AI learning from historical behavior (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/thenewstack.io\\/ai-powered-coding-developer-tool-trends-to-monitor-in-2025\\/?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"AI Coding Trends: Developer Tools To Watch in 2025 - The New Stack\\">The New Stack<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/pangea.ai\\/resources\\/how-ai-is-reshaping-software-development-trends-and-predictions-for-2025?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"How AI is Reshaping Software Development: Trends &amp; Predictions for 2025\\">Pangea<\\/a>, <a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.devscall.com\\/blog\\/ai-coding-in-2025?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"What is the Future of AI Coding in 2025 | DevsCall\\">devscall.com<\\/a>). This hyper\\u2011personalization boosts both speed and code quality.<\\/p><h3>4. <strong>Claude Opus 4.1 &amp; GPT\\u20115 Redefine Capabilities<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>Anthropic\\u2019s release of <strong>Claude Opus 4.1<\\/strong> enhances agentic reasoning, coding, and creative writing across domains (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/economictimes.indiatimes.com\\/tech\\/artificial-intelligence\\/anthropic-releases-claude-opus-4-1-amid-rival-chatgpts-advancements\\/articleshow\\/123143392.cms?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Anthropic releases Claude Opus 4.1 amid rival ChatGPT\'s advancements\\">The Economic Times<\\/a>). In parallel, a leaked GitHub blog revealed <strong>GPT\\u20115<\\/strong>, featuring four model variants including mini and nano versions optimized for complex reasoning and coding tasks with minimal prompts (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.theverge.com\\/news\\/752091\\/openai-gpt-5-model-announcement-github-leak?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"OpenAI\'s new GPT-5 models announced early by GitHub\\">The Verge<\\/a>).<\\/p><h3>5. <strong>GEO: Optimizing for Generative Search<\\/strong><\\/h3><p><strong>Generative Engine Optimization (GEO)<\\/strong> is evolving as a new SEO designed to ensure content is discoverable in AI-powered answers from ChatGPT, Gemini, Claude, and more (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/Generative_engine_optimization?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Generative engine optimization\\">Wikipedia<\\/a>). As AI agents increasingly serve as first-responder answers, publishers are adjusting metadata and structured content to retain visibility.<\\/p><h3>6. <strong>Agentic Web: AI Agents Everywhere<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>The rise of the <strong>\\u201cagentic web\\u201d<\\/strong>\\u2014a future internet filled with autonomous agents acting on behalf of users\\u2014is underway. These agents, informed by preferences and context, can manage tasks from scheduling to shopping and even content generation (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/en.wikipedia.org\\/wiki\\/Agentic_web?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Agentic web\\">Wikipedia<\\/a>). Developer tools are integrating more agentic behaviors across platforms.<\\/p><h3>7. <strong>Developer Roles Reimagined<\\/strong><\\/h3><p>GitHub CEO Thomas Dohmke recently declared that developers must <i>embrace AI or leave the industry<\\/i>, asserting that the future role of coders is becoming that of \\u201ccreative directors of code\\u201d\\u202frather than manual typists (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.businessinsider.com\\/github-ceo-developers-embrace-ai-or-get-out-2025-8?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"GitHub CEO delivers stark message to developers: Embrace AI or get out.\\">Business Insider<\\/a>). Tom Gruber warns that deep coders may be supplanted by those with strong reasoning and critical-thinking skills as GenAI grows stronger (<a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.theaustralian.com.au\\/business\\/siri-cocreator-tom-gruber-says-critical-thinking-philosophers-will-get-the-jobs-in\\/news-story\\/33de575417aabce649fd760d84e32599?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\" title=\\"Philosophers tipped to oust coding nerds in AI future\\">The Australian<\\/a>).<\\/p><hr><h3>\\ud83e\\udde0 Key Takeaways<\\/h3><ul><li><strong>Prompt fluency &amp; iteration skills<\\/strong> become more valuable than syntax-level mastery.<\\/li><li><strong>Critical thinking and architecture review<\\/strong> remain essential despite automated generation.<\\/li><li><strong>Security must be baked in early<\\/strong>; automated systems can hide vulnerabilities without proper oversight.<\\/li><li><strong>Adapt to generative discovery<\\/strong>: Optimize your content for citations by AI systems.<\\/li><li><strong>Be ready to evolve<\\/strong>: roles will shift toward strategy, design, and orchestration.<\\/li><\\/ul><hr><h3>\\ud83d\\udd0e Looking Forward<\\/h3><p>Mid\\u20112025 marks a watershed moment where AI doesn\\u2019t just assist code\\u2014it codes. The most successful developers will be those who orchestrate AI agents, refine output, and focus on system design, not syntax. As agentic tools proliferate and models like GPT\\u20115 and Claude Opus 4.1 push the boundaries, your edge lies in guiding AI thoughtfully, critically, and creatively.<\\/p><p>Want to explore code samples, prompt techniques, or tool comparisons next? Just say the word!<\\/p><ul><li><a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.theverge.com\\/news\\/752091\\/openai-gpt-5-model-announcement-github-leak?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\">The Verge<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\"https:\\/\\/economictimes.indiatimes.com\\/tech\\/artificial-intelligence\\/anthropic-releases-claude-opus-4-1-amid-rival-chatgpts-advancements\\/articleshow\\/123143392.cms?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\">The Economic Times<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.businessinsider.com\\/github-ceo-developers-embrace-ai-or-get-out-2025-8?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\">Business Insider<\\/a><\\/li><li><a href=\\"https:\\/\\/www.theaustralian.com.au\\/business\\/siri-cocreator-tom-gruber-says-critical-thinking-philosophers-will-get-the-jobs-in\\/news-story\\/33de575417aabce649fd760d84e32599?utm_source=chatgpt.com\\">The Australian<\\/a><\\/li><\\/ul>","gallery":null,"seo_meta":{"seo_title":null,"seo_description":null,"index":"index"},"seo_meta_image":null,"status":"published","categories":["2","6"],"image":"code\\/blog\\/blog03.jpg","tag":"[{\\"value\\":\\"Vietnam Developer\\"},{\\"value\\":\\"Open Source\\"},{\\"value\\":\\"JavaScript\\"}]","allow_comments":"0","submitter":"apply"}', 'updated', 'Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64; x64) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/138.0.0.0 Safari/537.36', '127.0.0.1', 1, 'Botble\\ACL\\Models\\User', 9, 'How to Integrate APIs in Node.js for Your Next Project